title: For Sale:  Kel-Tec PF-9 9mm
postcontent:
This is the current rendition of the PF-9. The deal includes three 7-round factory magazines and a pocket holster. The gun comes from the factory with one magazine and extras cost about $22. The holster is valued at about $10 and has only been used to protect the gun in storage. 

All included with the pistol:
3 7-rounnd factory magazines
1 pocket holster
1 trigger lock
1 extra magazine base pad with finger rest
1 extra Kel-Tec factory replacement extractor (new and unused)
1 extra Kel-Tec factory replacement extractor leaf spring (new and unused)
1 extra Kel-Tec factory replacement extractor screw (new and unused)
1 extra Kel-Tec factory replacement assembly pin (new and unused)
1 extra Kel-Tec factory replacement slide stop spring (new and unused)
Owners manual
Factory original hard case

This pistol cycles reliably with brass cased ammunition. Aluminum cases (such as CCI Blazer) have occasional failures to extract. Some European ammunition with hard primers (Sellier & Bellot, Herters Brass) will have occasional failures to ignite. Standard pressure American made factory loads work just fine. I have not used steel cased or +p ammunition in this pistol and would not recommend doing so.

The slide has been replaced by Kel-Tec. The original developed a hairline crack after about 400 rounds. The gun also has a new firing pin, extractor, and related hardware. The new slide assembly has only seen about 20 rounds.

A few notes on Kel-Tec's design:

Be sure to keep the screw on the extractor spring tight. If the screw loosens, the firing pin becomes loose and can fall out. I lost the first one prior to the slide replacement. I degreased the threads on the screw and the slide and applied some blue thread lock. I did not see any loosening after this operation on the original slide, and I have done the same thing with this slide. Just something to keep an eye on.

Also, make sure the spring that holds the assembly pin in place has enough tension on it. If the spring is not securely holding the assembly pin in place, the slide can shear the head of the pin off. Kel-Tec is pretty good about sending replacements, but it's an annoying feature of their design. 

The gun has been cleaned and maintained properly. It has spent most of its existence in the safe.

Buyer must show a Wisconsin Driver's License and sign a bill of sale. A Wisconsin Concealed Carry License is a plus. I can meet people in the Fennimore or Platteville areas.

title: Want To Buy:  Ammo shortage update
postcontent: The Motley Fool is a stockbroker site where trends are charted and stock market advice is given.  Check out their story on the ammo crises.  The article I just read says Cabelas and other big chains are showing a big decrease in ammo sales, and so their stock value will go down.  He says the only remaining shortage is 22, 22 mag and 9mm.  I was in Walmart yesterday and shelves were the fullest I have seen in more than 2 years, everything but 22 and 22 mag and they had plenty of 9mm.  People have stocked up on all the hunting calibers and pistol calibers.  What that means is when big calibers are no longer being sold,  the 22s and 9mms will be where the manufacturers go to keep up profits.  The bottom line is the 22/22 mag shortage is 3-6 months from being totally over.  Sure  many of us will hoard a few, but sooner or later the mass production will fill every cupboard and they will be on shelves 7 days a week.  Read the article, by summer 22s will be available everyday......FWIW
